05112nam a22007455i 9781503607491DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202019cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2018019452  a97815036074917 a10.1515/97815036074912doi  a(DE-B1597)563657  a(OCoLC)1178769837  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aHC415.4.Z9bP87 2019 4aHC415.4.Z9bP87 2019 7aHIS0260002bisacsh04a338.95671 aPursley, Sara, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFamiliar Futures :bTime, Selfhood, and Sovereignty in Iraq /cSara Pursley. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Middle Eastern and Islamic Societies and Cultures00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration and Translation -- tIntroduction: Iraqi Futures and the Age of Development -- t1. Sovereignty, Violence, and the Dual Mandate -- t2. Determining a Self -- t3. The Gendering of School Time -- t4. The Stage of Adolescence and the Marriage Crisis -- t5. The Family Farm and the Peculiar Futurist Perspective of Development -- t6. Revolutionary Time and Wasted Time -- t7. Law and the Post-Revolutionary Self -- tEpilogue: Postcolonial Heterotemporalities -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIraq was the first postcolonial state recognized as legally sovereign by the League of Nations amid the twentieth-century wave of decolonization movements. It also emerged as an early laboratory of development projects designed by Iraqi intellectuals, British colonial officials, American modernization theorists, and postwar international agencies. Familiar Futures considers how such projects—from the country's creation under British mandate rule in 1920 through the 1958 revolution to the first Ba'th coup in 1963—reshaped Iraqi everyday habits, desires, and familial relations in the name of a developed future. Sara Pursley investigates how Western and Iraqi policymakers promoted changes in schooling, land ownership, and family law to better differentiate Iraq's citizens by class, sex, and age. Peasants were resettled on isolated family farms; rural boys received education limited to training in agricultural skills; girls were required to take home economics courses; and adolescents were educated on the formation of proper families. Future-oriented discourses about the importance of sexual difference to Iraq's modernization worked paradoxically, deferring demands for political change in the present and reproducing existing capitalist relations. Ultimately, the book shows how certain goods—most obviously, democratic ideals—were repeatedly sacrificed in the name of the nation's economic development in an ever-receding future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aEconomic development projectsxSocial aspectszIraq. 0aEconomic developmentzIraqxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh  aIraq.  adecolonization.  adomesticity.  aeconomic development.  afamily reform.  agender.  amodernization theory.  asovereignty.  atemporality.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360